# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: markov-chains
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] In the mathematical theory of probability, an **absorbing Markov chain** is a Markov chain in which every state can reach an absorbing state.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] An absorbing state is a state that, once entered, cannot be left.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Like general Markov chains, there can be continuous-time absorbing Markov chains with an infinite state space.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] However, this article concentrates on the discrete-time discrete-state-space case.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] 2. it is possible to go from any state to at least one absorbing state in a finite number of steps.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] In an absorbing Markov chain, a state that is not absorbing is called transient.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Let an absorbing Markov chain with transition matrix *P* have *t* transient states and *r* absorbing states.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The rows of *P* represent sources, while columns represent destinations.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] where *Q* is a *t*-by-*t* matrix, *R* is a nonzero *t*-by-*r* matrix, **0** is an *r*-by-*t* zero matrix, and *I**r* is the *r*-by-*r* identity matrix.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Thus, *Q* describes the probability of transitioning from some transient state to another while *R* describes the probability of transitioning from some transient state to some absorbing state.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The probability of transitioning from *i* to *j* in exactly *k* steps is the (*i*,*j*)-entry of *P*k, further computed below.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] When considering only transient states, the probability is found in the upper left of *P*k, the (*i*,*j*)-entry of *Q*k.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] A basic property about an absorbing Markov chain is the expected number of visits to a transient state *j* starting from a transient state *i* (before being absorbed).
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] This can be established to be given by the (*i*, *j*) entry of so-called fundamental matrix *N*, obtained by summing *Q*k for all *k* (from 0 to ∞).
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] where *I**t* is the *t*-by-*t* identity matrix.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The computation of this formula is the matrix equivalent of the geometric series of scalars, ${\textstyle \sum }_{k=0}^{\infty }q^{k}={\tfrac {1}{1-q}}$ .
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] With the matrix *N* in hand, also other properties of the Markov chain are easy to obtain.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The expected number of steps before being absorbed in any absorbing state, when starting in transient state *i* can be computed via a sum over transient states.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] where **1** is a length-*t* column vector whose entries are all 1.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The number of columns of this matrix equals the number of absorbing states *r*.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] An approximation of those probabilities can also be obtained directly from the (*i*,*j*)-entry of $P^{k}$ for a large enough value of *k*, when *i* is the index of a transient, and *j* the index of an absorbing state.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] where *N*dg is the diagonal matrix with the same diagonal as *N*.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] where *N*sq is the Hadamard product of *N* with itself (i.e. each entry of *N* is squared).
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] where **t**sq is the Hadamard product of **t** with itself (i.e., as with *N*sq, each entry of **t** is squared).
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Consider the process of repeatedly flipping a fair coin until the sequence (heads, tails, heads) appears.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The first state represents the empty string, the second state the string "H", the third state the string "HT", and the fourth state the string "HTH".
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Although in reality, the coin flips cease after the string "HTH" is generated, the perspective of the absorbing Markov chain is that the process has transitioned into the absorbing state representing the string "HTH" and, therefore, cannot leave.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Therefore, the expected number of coin flips before observing the sequence (heads, tails, heads) is 10, the entry for the state representing the empty string.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Games based entirely on chance can be modeled by an absorbing Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] A classic example of this is the ancient Indian board game Snakes and Ladders.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] The graph on the left plots the probability mass in the lone absorbing state that represents the final square as the transition matrix is raised to larger and larger powers.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] To determine the expected number of turns to complete the game, compute the vector **t** as described above and examine **t**start, which is approximately 39.2.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Infectious disease testing, either of blood products or in medical clinics, is often taught as an example of an absorbing Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) model for HIV and for hepatitis B, for example, illustrates the property that absorbing Markov chains can lead to the detection of disease, versus the loss of detection through other means.
[src:markov-chains/absorbing-markov-chain] In the standard CDC model, the Markov chain has five states, a state in which the individual is uninfected, then a state with infected but undetectable virus, a state with detectable virus, and absorbing states of having quit/been lost from the clinic, or of having been detected (the goal).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In probability theory, a **hidden Markov model** (**HMM**) is a Markov model in which the observations are dependent on a latent (or *hidden*) Markov process (referred to as X ).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] An HMM requires that there be an observable process Y whose outcomes depend on the outcomes of X in a known way.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Since X cannot be observed directly, the goal is to learn about state of X by observing Y .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Estimation of the parameters in an HMM can be performed using maximum likelihood estimation.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] For linear chain HMMs, the Baum–Welch algorithm can be used to estimate parameters.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Let $X_{n}$ and $Y_{n}$ be discrete-time stochastic processes and $n\geq 1$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Let $X_{t}$ and $Y_{t}$ be continuous-time stochastic processes.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In its discrete form, a hidden Markov process can be visualized as a generalization of the urn problem with replacement (where each item from the urn is returned to the original urn before the next step).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In a room that is not visible to an observer there is a genie.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The room contains urns X1, X2, X3, ... each of which contains a known mix of balls, with each ball having a unique label y1, y2, y3, ... .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The genie chooses an urn in that room and randomly draws a ball from that urn.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It then puts the ball onto a conveyor belt, where the observer can observe the sequence of the balls but not the sequence of urns from which they were drawn.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Therefore, this is called a Markov process.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It can be described by the upper part of Figure 1.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The Markov process cannot be observed, only the sequence of labeled balls, thus this arrangement is called a *hidden Markov process*.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This is illustrated by the lower part of the diagram shown in Figure 1, where one can see that balls y1, y2, y3, y4 can be drawn at each state.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Even if the observer knows the composition of the urns and has just observed a sequence of three balls, *e.g.* y1, y2 and y3 on the conveyor belt, the observer still cannot be *sure* which urn (*i.e.*, at which state) the genie has drawn the third ball from.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] However, the observer can work out other information, such as the likelihood that the third ball came from each of the urns.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Consider two friends, Alice and Bob, who live far apart from each other and who talk together daily over the telephone about what they did that day.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Bob is only interested in three activities: walking in the park, shopping, and cleaning his apartment.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The choice of what to do is determined exclusively by the weather on a given day.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Alice has no definite information about the weather, but she knows general trends.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Based on what Bob tells her he did each day, Alice tries to guess what the weather must have been like.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Alice believes that the weather operates as a discrete Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] There are two states, "Rainy" and "Sunny", but she cannot observe them directly, that is, they are *hidden* from her.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] On each day, there is a certain chance that Bob will perform one of the following activities, depending on the weather: "walk", "shop", or "clean".
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Since Bob tells Alice about his activities, those are the *observations*.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The entire system is that of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Alice knows the general weather trends in the area, and what Bob likes to do on average.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In other words, the parameters of the HMM are known.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In this piece of code, `start_probability` represents Alice's belief about which state the HMM is in when Bob first calls her (all she knows is that it tends to be rainy on average).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The particular probability distribution used here is not the equilibrium one, which is (given the transition probabilities) approximately `{'Rainy': 0.57, 'Sunny': 0.43}`.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The `transition_probability` represents the change of the weather in the underlying Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In this example, there is only a 30% chance that tomorrow will be sunny if today is rainy.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The `emission_probability` represents how likely Bob is to perform a certain activity on each day.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] If it is rainy, there is a 50% chance that he is cleaning his apartment; if it is sunny, there is a 60% chance that he is outside for a walk.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The diagram below shows the general architecture of an instantiated HMM.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Each oval shape represents a random variable that can adopt any of a number of values.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The random variable *x*(*t*) is the hidden state at time t (with the model from the above diagram, *x*(*t*) ∈ {‍*x*1, *x*2, *x*3‍}).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The arrows in the diagram (often called a trellis diagram) denote conditional dependencies.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] From the diagram, it is clear that the conditional probability distribution of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) at time t, given the values of the hidden variable x at all times, depends *only* on the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t* − 1); the values at time *t* − 2 and before have no influence.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Similarly, the value of the observed variable *y*(*t*) depends on only the value of the hidden variable *x*(*t*) (both at time t).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In the standard type of hidden Markov model considered here, the state space of the hidden variables is discrete, while the observations themselves can either be discrete (typically generated from a categorical distribution) or continuous (typically from a Gaussian distribution).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The parameters of a hidden Markov model are of two types, *transition probabilities* and *emission probabilities* (also known as *output probabilities*).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The transition probabilities control the way the hidden state at time t is chosen given the hidden state at time *t* − 1.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The hidden state space is assumed to consist of one of N possible values, modelled as a categorical distribution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The set of transition probabilities for transitions from any given state must sum to 1.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Thus, the *N* × *N* matrix of transition probabilities is a Markov matrix.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Because any transition probability can be determined once the others are known, there are a total of *N*(*N* − 1) transition parameters.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In addition, for each of the N possible states, there is a set of emission probabilities governing the distribution of the observed variable at a particular time given the state of the hidden variable at that time.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The size of this set depends on the nature of the observed variable.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] For example, if the observed variable is discrete with M possible values, governed by a categorical distribution, there will be *M* − 1 separate parameters, for a total of *N*(*M* − 1) emission parameters over all hidden states.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Several inference problems are associated with hidden Markov models, as outlined below.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The task is to compute in a best way, given the parameters of the model, the probability of a particular output sequence.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Applying the principle of dynamic programming, this problem, too, can be handled efficiently using the forward algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] A number of related tasks ask about the probability of one or more of the latent variables, given the model's parameters and a sequence of observations $y(1),\dots ,y(t)$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The task is to compute, given the model's parameters and a sequence of observations, the distribution over hidden states of the last latent variable at the end of the sequence, i.e. to compute $P(x(t)\mid y(1),\dots ,y(t))$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This task is used when the sequence of latent variables is thought of as the underlying states that a process moves through at a sequence of points in time, with corresponding observations at each point.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Then, it is natural to ask about the state of the process at the end.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This problem can be handled efficiently using the forward algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] An example is when the algorithm is applied to a Hidden Markov Network to determine $\mathrm {P} {\big (}h_{t}\mid v_{1:t}{\big )}$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This is similar to filtering but asks about the distribution of a latent variable somewhere in the middle of a sequence, i.e. to compute $P(x(k)\mid y(1),\dots ,y(t))$ for some $k<t$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] From the perspective described above, this can be thought of as the probability distribution over hidden states for a point in time *k* in the past, relative to time *t*.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The forward-backward algorithm is a good method for computing the smoothed values for all hidden state variables.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The task, unlike the previous two, asks about the joint probability of the *entire* sequence of hidden states that generated a particular sequence of observations (see illustration on the right).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This task is generally applicable when HMM's are applied to different sorts of problems from those for which the tasks of filtering and smoothing are applicable.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] An example is part-of-speech tagging, where the hidden states represent the underlying parts of speech corresponding to an observed sequence of words.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In this case, what is of interest is the entire sequence of parts of speech, rather than simply the part of speech for a single word, as filtering or smoothing would compute.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This task requires finding a maximum over all possible state sequences, and can be solved efficiently by the Viterbi algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] For some of the above problems, it may also be interesting to ask about statistical significance.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] What is the probability that a sequence drawn from some null distribution will have an HMM probability (in the case of the forward algorithm) or a maximum state sequence probability (in the case of the Viterbi algorithm) at least as large as that of a particular output sequence?
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] When an HMM is used to evaluate the relevance of a hypothesis for a particular output sequence, the statistical significance indicates the false positive rate associated with failing to reject the hypothesis for the output sequence.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The parameter learning task in HMMs is to find, given an output sequence or a set of such sequences, the best set of state transition and emission probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The task is usually to derive the maximum likelihood estimate of the parameters of the HMM given the set of output sequences.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] No tractable algorithm is known for solving this problem exactly, but a local maximum likelihood can be derived efficiently using the Baum–Welch algorithm or the Baldi–Chauvin algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The Baum–Welch algorithm is a special case of the expectation-maximization algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] If the HMMs are used for time series prediction, more sophisticated Bayesian inference methods, like Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampling are proven to be favorable over finding a single maximum likelihood model both in terms of accuracy and stability.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Since MCMC imposes significant computational burden, in cases where computational scalability is also of interest, one may alternatively resort to variational approximations to Bayesian inference, e.g.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Indeed, approximate variational inference offers computational efficiency comparable to expectation-maximization, while yielding an accuracy profile only slightly inferior to exact MCMC-type Bayesian inference.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] HMMs can be applied in many fields where the goal is to recover a data sequence that is not immediately observable (but other data that depend on the sequence are).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Hidden Markov models were described in a series of statistical papers by Leonard E.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Baum and other authors in the second half of the 1960s.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] One of the first applications of HMMs was speech recognition, starting in the mid-1970s.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] From the linguistics point of view, hidden Markov models are equivalent to stochastic regular grammar.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In the second half of the 1980s, HMMs began to be applied to the analysis of biological sequences, in particular DNA.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Since then, they have become ubiquitous in the field of bioinformatics.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In the hidden Markov models considered above, the state space of the hidden variables is discrete, while the observations themselves can either be discrete (typically generated from a categorical distribution) or continuous (typically from a Gaussian distribution).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Hidden Markov models can also be generalized to allow continuous state spaces.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Examples of such models are those where the Markov process over hidden variables is a linear dynamical system, with a linear relationship among related variables and where all hidden and observed variables follow a Gaussian distribution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Nowadays, inference in hidden Markov models is performed in nonparametric settings, where the dependency structure enables identifiability of the model and the learnability limits are still under exploration.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The above algorithms implicitly assume a uniform prior distribution over the transition probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] However, it is also possible to create hidden Markov models with other types of prior distributions.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] An obvious candidate, given the categorical distribution of the transition probabilities, is the Dirichlet distribution, which is the conjugate prior distribution of the categorical distribution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Typically, a symmetric Dirichlet distribution is chosen, reflecting ignorance about which states are inherently more likely than others.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The single parameter of this distribution (termed the *concentration parameter*) controls the relative density or sparseness of the resulting transition matrix.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] A choice of 1 yields a uniform distribution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Values greater than 1 produce a dense matrix, in which the transition probabilities between pairs of states are likely to be nearly equal.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Values less than 1 result in a sparse matrix in which, for each given source state, only a small number of destination states have non-negligible transition probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It is also possible to use a two-level prior Dirichlet distribution, in which one Dirichlet distribution (the upper distribution) governs the parameters of another Dirichlet distribution (the lower distribution), which in turn governs the transition probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The upper distribution governs the overall distribution of states, determining how likely each state is to occur; its concentration parameter determines the density or sparseness of states.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The parameters of models of this sort, with non-uniform prior distributions, can be learned using Gibbs sampling or extended versions of the expectation-maximization algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] An extension of the previously described hidden Markov models with Dirichlet priors uses a Dirichlet process in place of a Dirichlet distribution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This type of model allows for an unknown and potentially infinite number of states.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It is common to use a two-level Dirichlet process, similar to the previously described model with two levels of Dirichlet distributions.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Such a model is called a *hierarchical Dirichlet process hidden Markov model*, or *HDP-HMM* for short.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It was originally described under the name "Infinite Hidden Markov Model" and was further formalized in "Hierarchical Dirichlet Processes".
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] A different type of extension uses a discriminative model in place of the generative model of standard HMMs.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This type of model directly models the conditional distribution of the hidden states given the observations, rather than modeling the joint distribution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] An example of this model is the so-called *maximum entropy Markov model* (MEMM), which models the conditional distribution of the states using logistic regression (also known as a "maximum entropy model").
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The advantage of this type of model is that arbitrary features (i.e. functions) of the observations can be modeled, allowing domain-specific knowledge of the problem at hand to be injected into the model.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Furthermore, there is no need for these features to be statistically independent of each other, as would be the case if such features were used in a generative model.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Finally, arbitrary features over pairs of adjacent hidden states can be used rather than simple transition probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantages of such models are: (1) The types of prior distributions that can be placed on hidden states are severely limited; (2) It is not possible to predict the probability of seeing an arbitrary observation.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This second limitation is often not an issue in practice, since many common usages of HMM's do not require such predictive probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] A variant of the previously described discriminative model is the linear-chain conditional random field.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This uses an undirected graphical model (aka Markov random field) rather than the directed graphical models of MEMM's and similar models.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The advantage of this type of model is that it does not suffer from the so-called *label bias* problem of MEMM's, and thus may make more accurate predictions.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantage is that training can be slower than for MEMM's.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Yet another variant is the *factorial hidden Markov model*, which allows for a single observation to be conditioned on the corresponding hidden variables of a set of K independent Markov chains, rather than a single Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It is equivalent to a single HMM, with $N^{K}$ states (assuming there are N states for each chain), and therefore, learning in such a model is difficult: for a sequence of length T , a straightforward Viterbi algorithm has complexity $O(N^{2K}\,T)$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] To find an exact solution, a junction tree algorithm could be used, but it results in an $O(N^{K+1}\,K\,T)$ complexity.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In practice, approximate techniques, such as variational approaches, could be used.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The disadvantage of such models is that dynamic-programming algorithms for training them have an $O(N^{K}\,T)$ running time, for K adjacent states and T total observations (i.e. a length- T Markov chain).
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This extension has been widely used in bioinformatics, in the modeling of DNA sequences.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Another recent extension is the *triplet Markov model*, in which an auxiliary underlying process is added to model some data specificities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Many variants of this model have been proposed.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] One should also mention the interesting link that has been established between the *theory of evidence* and the *triplet Markov models* and which allows to fuse data in Markovian context and to model nonstationary data.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Finally, a different rationale towards addressing the problem of modeling nonstationary data by means of hidden Markov models was suggested in 2012.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] It consists in employing a small recurrent neural network (RNN), specifically a reservoir network, to capture the evolution of the temporal dynamics in the observed data.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This information, encoded in the form of a high-dimensional vector, is used as a conditioning variable of the HMM state transition probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Under such a setup, eventually is obtained a nonstationary HMM, the transition probabilities of which evolve over time in a manner that is inferred from the data, in contrast to some unrealistic ad-hoc model of temporal evolution.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] In 2023, two innovative algorithms were introduced for the Hidden Markov Model.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] These algorithms enable the computation of the posterior distribution of the HMM without the necessity of explicitly modeling the joint distribution, utilizing only the conditional distributions.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Unlike traditional methods such as the Forward-Backward and Viterbi algorithms, which require knowledge of the joint law of the HMM and can be computationally intensive to learn, the Discriminative Forward-Backward and Discriminative Viterbi algorithms circumvent the need for the observation's law.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] This breakthrough allows the HMM to be applied as a discriminative model, offering a more efficient and versatile approach to leveraging Hidden Markov Models in various applications.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The model suitable in the context of longitudinal data is named latent Markov model.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The basic version of this model has been extended to include individual covariates, random effects and to model more complex data structures such as multilevel data.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Given a Markov transition matrix and an invariant distribution on the states, a probability measure can be imposed on the set of subshifts.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] For example, consider the Markov chain given on the right on the states $A,B_{1},B_{2}$ , with invariant distribution $\pi =(2/7,4/7,1/7)$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] By ignoring the distinction between $B_{1},B_{2}$ , this space of subshifts is projected on $A,B_{1},B_{2}$ into another space of subshifts on $A,B$ , and this projection also projects the probability measure down to a probability measure on the subshifts on $A,B$ .
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] The curious thing is that the probability measure on the subshifts on $A,B$ is not created by a Markov chain on $A,B$ , not even multiple orders.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Intuitively, this is because if one observes a long sequence of $B^{n}$ , then one would become increasingly sure that the $\Pr(A\mid B^{n})\to {\frac {2}{3}}$ , meaning that the observable part of the system can be affected by something infinitely in the past.
[src:markov-chains/hidden-markov-model] Conversely, there exists a space of subshifts on 6 symbols, projected to subshifts on 2 symbols, such that any Markov measure on the smaller subshift has a preimage measure that is not Markov of any order (example 2.6).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In probability theory and statistics, a **Markov chain** or **Markov process** is a stochastic process describing a sequence of possible events in which the probability of each event depends only on the state attained in the previous event.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Informally, this may be thought of as, "What happens next depends only on the state of affairs *now*." A countably infinite sequence, in which the chain moves state at discrete time steps, gives a discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time process is called a continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes are named in honor of the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Markov chains have many applications as statistical models of real-world processes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The adjectives *Markovian* and *Markov* are used to describe something that is related to a Markov process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Markov process is a stochastic process that satisfies the Markov property (sometimes characterized as "memorylessness").
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In simpler terms, it is a process for which predictions can be made regarding future outcomes based solely on its present state and—most importantly—such predictions are just as good as the ones that could be made knowing the process's full history.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In other words, conditional on the present state of the system, its future and past states are independent.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is a type of Markov process that has either a discrete state space or a discrete index set (often representing time), but the precise definition of a Markov chain varies.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The system's state space and time parameter index need to be specified.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Note that there is no definitive agreement in the literature on the use of some of the terms that signify special cases of Markov processes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Usually the term "Markov chain" is reserved for a process with a discrete set of times, that is, a **discrete-time Markov chain (DTMC)**, but a few authors use the term "Markov process" to refer to a **continuous-time Markov chain (CTMC)** without explicit mention.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In addition, there are other extensions of Markov processes that are referred to as such but do not necessarily fall within any of these four categories (see Markov model).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Moreover, the time index need not necessarily be real-valued; like with the state space, there are conceivable processes that move through index sets with other mathematical constructs.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Notice that the general state space continuous-time Markov chain is general to such a degree that it has no designated term.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] While the time parameter is usually discrete, the state space of a Markov chain does not have any generally agreed-on restrictions: the term may refer to a process on an arbitrary state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] However, many applications of Markov chains employ finite or countably infinite state spaces, which have a more straightforward statistical analysis.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Besides time-index and state-space parameters, there are many other variations, extensions and generalizations (see Variations).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] For simplicity, most of this article concentrates on the discrete-time, discrete state-space case, unless mentioned otherwise.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The changes of state of the system are called transitions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The probabilities associated with various state changes are called transition probabilities.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The process is characterized by a state space, a transition matrix describing the probabilities of particular transitions, and an initial state (or initial distribution) across the state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] By convention, we assume all possible states and transitions have been included in the definition of the process, so there is always a next state, and the process does not terminate.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A discrete-time random process involves a system which is in a certain state at each step, with the state changing randomly between steps.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The steps are often thought of as moments in time, but they can equally well refer to physical distance or any other discrete measurement.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Formally, the steps are the integers or natural numbers, and the random process is a mapping of these to states.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The Markov property states that the conditional probability distribution for the system at the next step (and in fact at all future steps) depends only on the current state of the system, and not additionally on the state of the system at previous steps.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since the system changes randomly, it is generally impossible to predict with certainty the state of a Markov chain at a given point in the future.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] However, the statistical properties of the system's future can be predicted.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In many applications, it is these statistical properties that are important.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Markov studied Markov processes in the early 20th century, publishing his first paper on the topic in 1906.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Markov processes in continuous time were discovered long before his work in the early 20th century in the form of the Poisson process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Markov was interested in studying an extension of independent random sequences, motivated by a disagreement with Pavel Nekrasov who claimed independence was necessary for the weak law of large numbers to hold.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Markov later used Markov chains to study the distribution of vowels in Eugene Onegin, written by Alexander Pushkin, and proved a central limit theorem for such chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In 1912 Henri Poincaré studied Markov chains on finite groups with an aim to study card shuffling.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Other early uses of Markov chains include a diffusion model, introduced by Paul and Tatyana Ehrenfest in 1907, and a branching process, introduced by Francis Galton and Henry William Watson in 1873, preceding the work of Markov.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] After the work of Galton and Watson, it was later revealed that their branching process had been independently discovered and studied around three decades earlier by Irénée-Jules Bienaymé.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Starting in 1928, Maurice Fréchet became interested in Markov chains, eventually resulting in him publishing in 1938 a detailed study on Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Andrey Kolmogorov developed in a 1931 paper a large part of the early theory of continuous-time Markov processes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov was partly inspired by Louis Bachelier's 1900 work on fluctuations in the stock market as well as Norbert Wiener's work on Einstein's model of Brownian movement.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] He introduced and studied a particular set of Markov processes known as diffusion processes, where he derived a set of differential equations describing the processes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Independent of Kolmogorov's work, Sydney Chapman derived in a 1928 paper an equation, now called the Chapman–Kolmogorov equation, in a less mathematically rigorous way than Kolmogorov, while studying Brownian movement.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The differential equations are now called the Kolmogorov equations or the Kolmogorov–Chapman equations.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Other mathematicians who contributed significantly to the foundations of Markov processes include William Feller, starting in 1930s, and then later Eugene Dynkin, starting in the 1950s.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that there is a coin purse containing five coins worth 25¢ (quarters), five coins worth 10¢ (dimes) and five coins worth 5¢ (nickels).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] One by one, coins are randomly drawn from the purse and are set on a table.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If $X_{n}$ represents the total value of the coins set on the table after n draws, with $X_{0}=0$ , then the sequence $\{X_{n}:n\in \mathbb {N} \}$ is *not* a Markov process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] To see why this is the case, suppose that in the first six draws, all five nickels and a quarter are drawn.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If we know not just $X_{6}$ , but the earlier values as well, then we can determine which coins have been drawn, and we know that the next coin will not be a nickel; so we can determine that $X_{7}\geq \$0.60$ with probability 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] But if we do not know the earlier values, then based only on the value $X_{6}$ we might guess that we had drawn four dimes and two nickels, in which case it would certainly be possible to draw another nickel next.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Thus, our guesses about $X_{7}$ are impacted by our knowledge of values prior to $X_{6}$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] However, it is possible to model this scenario as a Markov process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Instead of defining $X_{n}$ to represent the *total value* of the coins on the table, we could define $X_{n}$ to represent the *count* of the various coin types on the table.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] For instance, $X_{6}=1,0,5$ could be defined to represent the state where there is one quarter, zero dimes, and five nickels on the table after 6 one-by-one draws.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] This new model could be represented by $6\times 6\times 6=216$ possible states, where each state represents the number of coins of each type (from 0 to 5) that are on the table.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Suppose that the first draw results in state $X_{1}=0,1,0$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The probability of achieving $X_{2}$ now depends on $X_{1}$ ; for example, the state $X_{2}=1,0,1$ is not possible.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] After the second draw, the third draw depends on which coins have so far been drawn, but no longer only on the coins that were drawn for the first state (since probabilistically important information has since been added to the scenario).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In this way, the likelihood of the $X_{n}=i,j,k$ state depends exclusively on the outcome of the $X_{n-1}=\ell ,m,p$ state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The possible values of *X**i* form a countable set *S* called the state space of the chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since each row of **P** sums to one and all elements are non-negative, **P** is a right stochastic matrix.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] is a normalized ( ${\textstyle \sum _{i}\pi _{i}=1}$ ) multiple of a left eigenvector **e** of the transition matrix **P** with an eigenvalue of 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If there is more than one unit eigenvector then a weighted sum of the corresponding stationary states is also a stationary state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] But for a Markov chain one is usually more interested in a stationary state that is the limit of the sequence of distributions for some initial distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The values of a stationary distribution $\textstyle \pi _{i}$ are associated with the state space of **P** and its eigenvectors have their relative proportions preserved.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since the components of π are positive and the constraint that their sum is unity can be rewritten as ${\textstyle \sum _{i}1\cdot \pi _{i}=1}$ we see that the dot product of π with a vector whose components are all 1 is unity and that π lies on a simplex.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is time-homogeneous, then the transition matrix **P** is the same after each step, so the *k*-step transition probability can be computed as the *k*-th power of the transition matrix, **P***k*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If the Markov chain is irreducible and aperiodic, then there is a unique stationary distribution π.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] where **1** is the column vector with all entries equal to 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] This is stated by the Perron–Frobenius theorem.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If, by whatever means, ${\textstyle \lim _{k\to \infty }\mathbf {P} ^{k}}$ is found, then the stationary distribution of the Markov chain in question can be easily determined for any starting distribution, as will be explained below.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Because there are a number of different special cases to consider, the process of finding this limit if it exists can be a lengthy task.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] However, there are many techniques that can assist in finding this limit.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size *n*, and **0***n*,*n* is the zero matrix of size *n*×*n*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Multiplying together stochastic matrices always yields another stochastic matrix, so **Q** must be a stochastic matrix (see the definition above).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] It is sometimes sufficient to use the matrix equation above and the fact that **Q** is a stochastic matrix to solve for **Q**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Here is one method for doing so: first, define the function *f*(**A**) to return the matrix **A** with its right-most column replaced with all 1's.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] One thing to notice is that if **P** has an element **P***i*,*i* on its main diagonal that is equal to 1 and the *i*th row or column is otherwise filled with 0's, then that row or column will remain unchanged in all of the subsequent powers **P***k*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Hence, the *i*th row or column of **Q** will have the 1 and the 0's in the same positions as in **P**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] As stated earlier, from the equation ${\boldsymbol {\pi }}={\boldsymbol {\pi }}\mathbf {P} ,$ (if exists) the stationary (or steady state) distribution **π** is a left eigenvector of row stochastic matrix **P**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Then assuming that **P** is diagonalizable or equivalently that **P** has *n* linearly independent eigenvectors, speed of convergence is elaborated as follows.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Let **U** be the matrix of eigenvectors (each normalized to having an L2 norm equal to 1) where each column is a left eigenvector of **P** and let **Σ** be the diagonal matrix of left eigenvalues of **P**, that is, **Σ** = diag(*λ*1,*λ*2,*λ*3,...,*λ**n*).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since **P** is a row stochastic matrix, its largest left eigenvalue is 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If there is a unique stationary distribution, then the largest eigenvalue and the corresponding eigenvector is unique too (because there is no other **π** which solves the stationary distribution equation above).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Let **u***i* be the *i*-th column of **U** matrix, that is, **u***i* is the left eigenvector of **P** corresponding to λ*i*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If we multiply **x** with **P** from right and continue this operation with the results, in the end we get the stationary distribution **π**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since **π** is parallel to **u**1(normalized by L2 norm) and **π**(*k*) is a probability vector, **π**(*k*) approaches to **a**1 **u**1 = **π** as *k* → ∞ with a speed in the order of *λ*2/*λ*1 exponentially.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] This follows because $|\lambda _{2}|\geq \cdots \geq |\lambda _{n}|,$ hence *λ*2/*λ*1 is the dominant term.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The smaller the ratio is, the faster the convergence is.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Random noise in the state distribution **π** can also speed up this convergence to the stationary distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov chain $(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is defined by a finite or countable state space *S*, a transition rate matrix *Q* with dimensions equal to that of the state space and initial probability distribution defined on the state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] For *i* ≠ *j*, the elements *q**ij* are non-negative and describe the rate of the process transitions from state *i* to state *j*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The elements *q**ii* are chosen such that each row of the transition rate matrix sums to zero, while the row-sums of a probability transition matrix in a (discrete) Markov chain are all equal to one.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] There are three equivalent definitions of the process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Let $X_{t}$ be the random variable describing the state of the process at time *t*, and assume the process is in a state *i* at time *t*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Then, knowing $X_{t}=i$ , $X_{t+h}=j$ is independent of previous values $\left(X_{s}:s<t\right)$ , and as *h* → 0 for all *j* and for all *t*, $\Pr(X(t+h)=j\mid X(t)=i)=\delta _{ij}+q_{ij}h+o(h),$ where $\delta _{ij}$ is the Kronecker delta, using the little-o notation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The $q_{ij}$ can be seen as measuring how quickly the transition from *i* to *j* happens.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Define a discrete-time Markov chain *Y**n* to describe the *n*th jump of the process and variables *S*1, *S*2, *S*3, ... to describe holding times in each of the states where *S**i* follows the exponential distribution with rate parameter −*q**Y**i**Y**i*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] with initial condition P(0) is the identity matrix.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] "Locally interacting Markov chains" are Markov chains with an evolution that takes into account the state of other Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] This corresponds to the situation when the state space has a (Cartesian-) product form.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] See interacting particle system and stochastic cellular automata (probabilistic cellular automata).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] See for instance *Interaction of Markov Processes* or.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Many results for discrete-time Markov chains with finite state space can be generalized to chains with uncountable state space through Harris chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The use of Markov chains in Markov chain Monte Carlo methods covers cases where the process follows a continuous state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The definition of Markov processes in continuous time with general state space is more technical than the above.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A continuous-time Markov process $X=(X_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ is a stochastic process adapted to a filtration $\mathbb {F} =({\mathcal {F}}_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ with values in a locally compact Polish space $(S,{\mathcal {B}}(S))$ (e.g., $(\mathbb {R} ,{\mathcal {B}}(\mathbb {R} ))$ ).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The latter essentially ensures that the conditional expectations of $X_{t}$ are regular, which, in simple terms, means that they behave "nicely".
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The function $(t,x,A)\mapsto P_{t}(x,A)$ is the so-called *transition function* of X and $(P_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ the *transition semigroup* of the process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Transition functions are generalizations of the transition matrices used in the setting with finite state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] where $\delta _{x}$ is the Dirac-measure in x , and $X:\Omega \times [0,\infty )\to S$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Or, if no probability measure P has been specified, the above equation defines a measure $P^{x}:=P(\cdot \mid X_{0}=x)$ on $\sigma (X_{s}:s\geq 0)$ under which the process X started in x is a Markov process by construction.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In other words, Markov processes can be defined either as stochastic processes X on a filtered probability space, or indirectly in terms of a transition semigroup (i.e., the transition probabilities of the process), which induces a probability space under which X has the Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Two states are said to *communicate* with each other if both are reachable from one another by a sequence of transitions that have positive probability.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] This is an equivalence relation which yields a set of communicating classes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A class is *closed* if the probability of leaving the class is zero.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain is *irreducible* if there is one communicating class, the state space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* has period *k* if *k* is the greatest common divisor of the number of transitions by which *i* can be reached, starting from *i*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The state is *periodic* if $k>1$ ; otherwise $k=1$ and the state is *aperiodic*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *transient* if, starting from *i*, there is a non-zero probability that the chain will never return to *i*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] It is called *recurrent* (or *persistent*) otherwise.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] State *i* is *positive recurrent* if $M_{i}$ is finite and *null recurrent* otherwise.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Periodicity, transience, recurrence and positive and null recurrence are class properties — that is, if one state has the property then all states in its communicating class have the property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is called *absorbing* if there are no outgoing transitions from the state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since periodicity is a class property, if a Markov chain is irreducible, then all its states have the same period.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In particular, if one state is aperiodic, then the whole Markov chain is aperiodic.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If a finite Markov chain is irreducible, then all states are positive recurrent, and it has a unique stationary distribution given by $\pi _{i}=1/E[T_{i}]$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A state *i* is said to be *ergodic* if it is aperiodic and positive recurrent.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In other words, a state *i* is ergodic if it is recurrent, has a period of 1, and has finite mean recurrence time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If all states in an irreducible Markov chain are ergodic, then the chain is said to be ergodic.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Equivalently, there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] It can be shown that a finite state irreducible Markov chain is ergodic if it has an aperiodic state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Markov chain with more than one state and just one out-going transition per state is either not irreducible or not aperiodic, hence cannot be ergodic.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call any irreducible, positive recurrent Markov chains ergodic, even periodic ones.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In fact, merely irreducible Markov chains correspond to ergodic processes, defined according to ergodic theory.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Some authors call a matrix *primitive* if there exists some integer k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The *index of primitivity*, or *exponent*, of a regular matrix, is the smallest k such that all entries of $M^{k}$ are positive.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The exponent is purely a graph-theoretic property, since it depends only on whether each entry of M is zero or positive, and therefore can be found on a directed graph with $\mathrm {sign} (M)$ as its adjacency matrix.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] There are several combinatorial results about the exponent when there are finitely many states.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If a Markov chain has a stationary distribution, then it can be converted to a measure-preserving dynamical system: Let the probability space be $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {N} }$ , where $\Sigma$ is the set of all states for the Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Let the sigma-algebra on the probability space be generated by the cylinder sets.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Let the probability measure be generated by the stationary distribution, and the Markov chain transition.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Similarly we can construct such a dynamical system with $\Omega =\Sigma ^{\mathbb {Z} }$ instead.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Since *irreducible* Markov chains with finite state spaces have a unique stationary distribution, the above construction is unambiguous for irreducible Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In ergodic theory, a measure-preserving dynamical system is called *ergodic* if any measurable subset S such that $T^{-1}(S)=S$ implies $S=\emptyset$ or $\Omega$ (up to a null set).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Given a Markov chain with a stationary distribution that is strictly positive on all states, the Markov chain is *irreducible* if its corresponding measure-preserving dynamical system is *ergodic*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] In some cases, apparently non-Markovian processes may still have Markovian representations, constructed by expanding the concept of the "current" and "future" states.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] For example, let *X* be a non-Markovian process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Then define a process *Y*, such that each state of *Y* represents a time-interval of states of *X*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If *Y* has the Markov property, then it is a Markovian representation of *X*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] An example of a non-Markovian process with a Markovian representation is an autoregressive time series of order greater than one.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The *hitting time* is the time, starting in a given set of states, until the chain arrives in a given state or set of states.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The distribution of such a time period has a phase type distribution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The simplest such distribution is that of a single exponentially distributed transition.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] For a general Markov process X in continuous time (a CTMC or a process with general state space), the reverse process ${\overleftarrow {X}}=(X_{T-t})_{t\in [0,T]}$ from a fixed time $T>0$ is again a Markov process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] This follows directly from the Markov property: Informally speaking, the future and the past are independent given the present.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Under time-reversal, their roles are just interchanged.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] However, the reverse process is not time-homogeneous in general.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] If X is a CTMC, then by Kelly's lemma ${\overleftarrow {X}}$ has the same stationary distribution as the forward process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A chain is said to be *reversible* if the reversed process is the same as the forward process (in distribution).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Kolmogorov's criterion states that the necessary and sufficient condition for a Markov chain to be reversible is that the product of transition rates around a closed loop must be the same in both directions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] One method of finding the stationary probability distribution, π, of an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain, *Q*, is by first finding its **embedded Markov chain (EMC)**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Strictly speaking, the EMC is a regular discrete-time Markov chain, sometimes referred to as a **jump process**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Each element of the one-step transition probability matrix of the EMC, *S*, is denoted by *s**ij*, and represents the conditional probability of transitioning from state *i* into state *j*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] where *I* is the identity matrix and diag(*Q*) is the diagonal matrix formed by selecting the main diagonal from the matrix *Q* and setting all other elements to zero.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] with $\varphi$ being a row vector, such that all elements in $\varphi$ are greater than 0 and $\|\varphi \|_{1}$ = 1.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] (*S* may be periodic, even if *Q* is not.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Another discrete-time process that may be derived from a continuous-time Markov chain is a δ-skeleton—the (discrete-time) Markov chain formed by observing *X*(*t*) at intervals of δ units of time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The random variables *X*(0), *X*(δ), *X*(2δ), ... give the sequence of states visited by the δ-skeleton.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Markov models are used to model changing systems.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme is a special case of a Markov chain where the transition probability matrix has identical rows, which means that the next state is independent of even the current state (in addition to being independent of the past states).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Bernoulli scheme with only two possible states is known as a Bernoulli process.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Note, however, by the Ornstein isomorphism theorem, that every aperiodic and irreducible Markov chain is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; thus, one might equally claim that Markov chains are a "special case" of Bernoulli schemes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism generally requires a complicated recoding.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] The isomorphism theorem is even a bit stronger: it states that *any* stationary stochastic process is isomorphic to a Bernoulli scheme; the Markov chain is just one such example.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] When the Markov matrix is replaced by the adjacency matrix of a finite graph, the resulting shift is termed a **topological Markov chain** or a **subshift of finite type**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] A Markov matrix that is compatible with the adjacency matrix can then provide a measure on the subshift.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p01] Many chaotic dynamical systems are isomorphic to topological Markov chains; examples include diffeomorphisms of closed manifolds, the Prouhet–Thue–Morse system, the Chacon system, sofic systems, context-free systems and block-coding systems.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains have been employed in a wide range of topics across the natural and social sciences, and in technological applications.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] For example, a thermodynamic state operates under a probability distribution that is difficult or expensive to acquire.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Therefore, Markov Chain Monte Carlo method can be used to draw samples randomly from a black-box to approximate the probability distribution of attributes over a range of objects.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in lattice QCD simulations.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The enzyme (E) binds a substrate (S) and produces a product (P).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Each reaction is a state transition in a Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] A reaction network is a chemical system involving multiple reactions and chemical species.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The simplest stochastic models of such networks treat the system as a continuous time Markov chain with the state being the number of molecules of each species and with reactions modeled as possible transitions of the chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains and continuous-time Markov processes are useful in chemistry when physical systems closely approximate the Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] For example, imagine a large number *n* of molecules in solution in state A, each of which can undergo a chemical reaction to state B with a certain average rate.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Perhaps the molecule is an enzyme, and the states refer to how it is folded.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The state of any single enzyme follows a Markov chain, and since the molecules are essentially independent of each other, the number of molecules in state A or B at a time is *n* times the probability a given molecule is in that state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The classical model of enzyme activity, Michaelis–Menten kinetics, can be viewed as a Markov chain, where at each time step the reaction proceeds in some direction.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] While Michaelis-Menten is fairly straightforward, far more complicated reaction networks can also be modeled with Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm based on a Markov chain was also used to focus the fragment-based growth of chemicals in silico towards a desired class of compounds such as drugs or natural products.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] As a molecule is grown, a fragment is selected from the nascent molecule as the "current" state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] It is not aware of its past (that is, it is not aware of what is already bonded to it).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] It then transitions to the next state when a fragment is attached to it.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The transition probabilities are trained on databases of authentic classes of compounds.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Also, the growth (and composition) of copolymers may be modeled using Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Based on the reactivity ratios of the monomers that make up the growing polymer chain, the chain's composition may be calculated (for example, whether monomers tend to add in alternating fashion or in long runs of the same monomer).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Due to steric effects, second-order Markov effects may also play a role in the growth of some polymer chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Similarly, it has been suggested that the crystallization and growth of some epitaxial superlattice oxide materials can be accurately described by Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in various areas of biology.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used throughout information processing.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Such idealized models can capture many of the statistical regularities of systems.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Even without describing the full structure of the system perfectly, such signal models can make possible very effective data compression through entropy encoding techniques such as arithmetic coding.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] They also allow effective state estimation and pattern recognition.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains also play an important role in reinforcement learning.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also the basis for hidden Markov models, which are an important tool in such diverse fields as telephone networks (which use the Viterbi algorithm for error correction), speech recognition and bioinformatics (such as in rearrangements detection).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The LZMA lossless data compression algorithm combines Markov chains with Lempel-Ziv compression to achieve very high compression ratios.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are the basis for the analytical treatment of queues (queueing theory).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Agner Krarup Erlang initiated the subject in 1917.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] This makes them critical for optimizing the performance of telecommunications networks, where messages must often compete for limited resources (such as bandwidth).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Numerous queueing models use continuous-time Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The PageRank of a webpage as used by Google is defined by a Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] It is the probability to be at page i in the stationary distribution on the following Markov chain on all (known) webpages.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] If N is the number of known webpages, and a page i has $k_{i}$ outgoing links from it then it has transition probability ${\frac {\alpha }{k_{i}}}+{\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are linked to and ${\frac {1-\alpha }{N}}$ for all pages that are not linked to.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The parameter $\alpha$ is taken to be about 0.85.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov models have also been used to analyze web navigation behavior of users.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] A user's web link transition on a particular website can be modeled using first- or second-order Markov models and can be used to make predictions regarding future navigation and to personalize the web page for an individual user.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain methods have also become very important for generating sequences of random numbers to accurately reflect very complicated desired probability distributions, via a process called Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] In recent years this has revolutionized the practicability of Bayesian inference methods, allowing a wide range of posterior distributions to be simulated and their parameters found numerically.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are used in finance and economics to model a variety of different phenomena, including the distribution of income, the size distribution of firms, asset prices and market crashes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Champernowne built a Markov chain model of the distribution of income in 1953.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Simon and co-author Charles Bonini used a Markov chain model to derive a stationary Yule distribution of firm sizes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Louis Bachelier was the first to observe that stock prices followed a random walk.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The random walk was later seen as evidence in favor of the efficient-market hypothesis and random walk models were popular in the literature of the 1960s.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Regime-switching models of business cycles were popularized by James D.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Hamilton (1989), who used a Markov chain to model switches between periods of high and low GDP growth (or, alternatively, economic expansions and recessions).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] A more recent example is the Markov switching multifractal model of Laurent E.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Fisher, which builds upon the convenience of earlier regime-switching models.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] It uses an arbitrarily large Markov chain to drive the level of volatility of asset returns.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Dynamic macroeconomics makes heavy use of Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] An example is using Markov chains to exogenously model prices of equity (stock) in a general equilibrium setting.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Credit rating agencies produce annual tables of the transition probabilities for bonds of different credit ratings.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are generally used in describing path-dependent arguments, where current structural configurations condition future outcomes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] An example is the reformulation of the idea, originally due to Karl Marx's *Das Kapital*, tying economic development to the rise of capitalism.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are employed in algorithmic music composition, particularly in software such as Csound, Max, and SuperCollider.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] In a first-order chain, the states of the system become note or pitch values, and a probability vector for each note is constructed, completing a transition probability matrix (see below).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] An algorithm is constructed to produce output note values based on the transition matrix weightings, which could be MIDI note values, frequency (Hz), or any other desirable metric.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] A second-order Markov chain can be introduced by considering the current state *and* also the previous state, as indicated in the second table.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Higher, *n*th-order chains tend to "group" particular notes together, while 'breaking off' into other patterns and sequences occasionally.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] These higher-order chains tend to generate results with a sense of phrasal structure, rather than the 'aimless wandering' produced by a first-order system.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used structurally, as in Xenakis's Analogique A and B.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains are also used in systems which use a Markov model to react interactively to music input.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Usually musical systems need to enforce specific control constraints on the finite-length sequences they generate, but control constraints are not compatible with Markov models, since they induce long-range dependencies that violate the Markov hypothesis of limited memory.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] In order to overcome this limitation, a new approach has been proposed.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chains can be used to model many games of chance.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] The children's games Snakes and Ladders and "Hi Ho!
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Cherry-O", for example, are represented exactly by Markov chains.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] At each turn, the player starts in a given state (on a given square) and from there has fixed odds of moving to certain other states (squares).
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov chain models have been used in advanced baseball analysis since 1960, although their use is still rare.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Each half-inning of a baseball game fits the Markov chain state when the number of runners and outs are considered.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] During any at-bat, there are 24 possible combinations of number of outs and position of the runners.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Mark Pankin shows that Markov chain models can be used to evaluate runs created for both individual players as well as a team.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] He also discusses various kinds of strategies and play conditions: how Markov chain models have been used to analyze statistics for game situations such as bunting and base stealing and differences when playing on grass vs.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes can also be used to generate superficially real-looking text given a sample document.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Markov processes are used in a variety of recreational "parody generator" software (see dissociated press, Jeff Harrison, Mark V.
[src:markov-chains/markov-chain-p02] Several open-source text generation libraries using Markov chains exist.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] A **Markov decision process** (**MDP**) is a mathematical model for sequential decision making when outcomes are uncertain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] It is a type of stochastic decision process, and is often solved using the methods of stochastic dynamic programming.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Originating from operations research in the 1950s, MDPs have since gained recognition in a variety of fields, including ecology, economics, healthcare, telecommunications and reinforcement learning.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning utilizes the MDP framework to model the interaction between a learning agent and its environment.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In this framework, the interaction is characterized by states, actions, and rewards.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The MDP framework is designed to provide a simplified representation of key elements of artificial intelligence challenges.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] This modeling framework incorporates the understanding of cause and effect, the management of uncertainty and nondeterminism, and the pursuit of explicit goals.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The name comes from its connection to Markov chains, a concept developed by the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The "Markov" in "Markov decision process" refers to the underlying structure of state transitions that still follow the Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The process is called a "decision process" because it involves making decisions that influence these state transitions, extending the concept of a Markov chain into the realm of decision-making under uncertainty.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] A policy function $\pi$ is a (potentially probabilistic) mapping from state space ( S ) to action space ( A ).
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The goal in a Markov decision process is to find a good "policy" for the decision maker: a function $\pi$ that specifies the action $\pi (s)$ that the decision maker will choose when in state s .
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Once a Markov decision process is combined with a policy in this way, this fixes the action for each state and the resulting combination behaves like a Markov chain (since the action chosen in state s is completely determined by $\pi (s)$ ).
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] where $\ \gamma \$ is the discount factor satisfying $0\leq \ \gamma \ \leq \ 1$ , which is usually close to 1 (for example, $\gamma =1/(1+r)$ for some discount rate r ).
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] A lower discount factor makes the decision maker more short-sighted, in that it comparatively disregards the effect that following its current policy has at times lying further in the future.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Another possible, but strictly related, objective that is commonly used is the $H-$ step return.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] This time, instead of using a discount factor $\ \gamma \$ , the agent is interested only in the first H steps of the process, with each reward having the same weight.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Compared to the previous objective, the latter one is more used in Learning Theory.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] A policy that maximizes the function above is called an **optimal policy** and is usually denoted $\pi ^{*}$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] A particular MDP may have multiple distinct optimal policies.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Because of the Markov property, it can be shown that the optimal policy is a function of the current state, as assumed above.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] When $R_{a}(s,s')$ is deterministic, there will always exist an optimal policy $\pi ^{*}$ which is deterministic as well.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Assume that R is deterministic, meaning for constants $a,s,s'$ the value $R_{a}(s,s')$ is also constant.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] From inspection, notice that this fixed point is the value function associated to the following policy.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] By unrolling the Bellman recursion, one can show that $V^{*}$ is indeed optimal (simultaneously for all states) over the set of deterministic policies.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Consider the case where $\pi$ is probabilistic, meaning the action taken $a:=\pi (s)$ is a random variable.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] One can show any such non-deterministic policy is dominated by deterministic $\pi ^{*}$ as follows.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In many cases, it is difficult to represent the transition probability distributions, $P_{a}(s,s')$ , explicitly.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In such cases, a simulator can be used to model the MDP implicitly by providing samples from the transition distributions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] One common form of implicit MDP model is an episodic environment simulator that can be started from an initial state and yields a subsequent state and reward every time it receives an action input.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In this manner, trajectories of states, actions, and rewards, often called **episodes** may be produced.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Another form of simulator is a **generative model**, a single step simulator that can generate samples of the next state and reward given any state and action.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] (Note that this is a different meaning from the term generative model in the context of statistical classification.) In algorithms that are expressed using pseudocode, G is often used to represent a generative model.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] For example, the expression $s',r\gets G(s,a)$ might denote the action of sampling from the generative model where s and a are the current state and action, and $s'$ and r are the new state and reward.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Compared to an episodic simulator, a generative model has the advantage that it can yield data from any state, not only those encountered in a trajectory.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] These model classes form a hierarchy of information content: an explicit model trivially yields a generative model through sampling from the distributions, and repeated application of a generative model yields an episodic simulator.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In the opposite direction, it is only possible to learn approximate models through regression.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The type of model available for a particular MDP plays a significant role in determining which solution algorithms are appropriate.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] An example of MDP is the Pole-Balancing model, which comes from classic control theory.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Solutions for MDPs with finite state and action spaces may be found through a variety of methods such as dynamic programming.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The algorithms in this section apply to MDPs with finite state and action spaces and explicitly given transition probabilities and reward functions, but the basic concepts may be extended to handle other problem classes, for example using function approximation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Also, some processes with countably infinite state and action spaces can be *exactly* reduced to ones with finite state and action spaces.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The standard family of algorithms to calculate optimal policies for finite state and action MDPs requires storage for two arrays indexed by state: *value* V , which contains real values, and *policy* $\pi$ , which contains actions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] At the end of the algorithm, $\pi$ will contain the solution and $V(s)$ will contain the discounted sum of the rewards to be earned (on average) by following that solution from state s .
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The algorithm has two steps, (1) a value update and (2) a policy update, which are repeated in some order for all the states until no further changes take place.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Both recursively update a new estimation of the optimal policy and state value using an older estimation of those values.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Their order depends on the variant of the algorithm; one can also do them for all states at once or state by state, and more often to some states than others.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] As long as no state is permanently excluded from either of the steps, the algorithm will eventually arrive at the correct solution.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In value iteration (Bellman 1957), which is also called backward induction, the $\pi$ function is not used; instead, the value of $\pi (s)$ is calculated within $V(s)$ whenever it is needed.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Value iteration starts at $i=0$ and $V_{0}$ as a guess of the value function.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] It then iterates, repeatedly computing $V_{i+1}$ for all states s , until V converges with the left-hand side equal to the right-hand side (which is the "Bellman equation" for this problem).
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Lloyd Shapley's 1953 paper on stochastic games included as a special case the value iteration method for MDPs, but this was recognized only later on.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Value iteration is guaranteed to converge for $\gamma <1$ by the Banach fixed-point theorem.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The Banach fixed-point theorem states that a given contraction mapping has a unique fixed point; further, one can asymptotically approach this fixed points by iterated application of the contraction mapping.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] It then suffices to show that value iteration is a contraction mapping, which is shown below for $\gamma <1$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In policy iteration, one first performs *Value Determination* by solving for V from the linear system described in step one, then performs *Policy Improvement* by computing $\pi$ as in step two, then repeats both steps until the policy converges.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Since policy iteration effectively interleaves a linear inverse problem with a nonlinear operation, it may interpreted as a type of relaxation method.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] This variant has the advantage that there is a definite stopping condition.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Since there is a unique solution V for each policy $\pi$ , the algorithm is completed once the *Policy Improvement* produces the same policy twice consecutively.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] While there are situations where policy iteration may be faster than value iteration (e.g. when the action space is significantly larger than the state space), policy iteration is usually slower than value iteration for a large number of possible states.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In modified policy iteration (van Nunen 1976; Puterman & Shin 1978), step one is repeated several times, and then step two is performed once.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Then step one is again repeated several times and so on.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Algorithms for finding optimal policies with time complexity polynomial in the size of the problem representation exist for finite MDPs.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Thus, decision problems based on MDPs are in computational complexity class P.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] However, due to the curse of dimensionality, the size of the problem representation is often exponential in the number of state and action variables, limiting exact solution techniques to problems that have a compact representation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] A Markov decision process is a stochastic game with only one player.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The solution above assumes that the state s is known when action is to be taken; otherwise $\pi (s)$ cannot be calculated.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] When this assumption is not true, the problem is called a partially observable Markov decision process or POMDP.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Constrained Markov decision processes (CMDPS) are extensions to Markov decision process (MDPs).
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] There are three fundamental differences between MDPs and CMDPs.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The method of Lagrange multipliers applies to CMDPs.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Many Lagrangian-based algorithms have been developed.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] There are a number of applications for CMDPs.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] It has recently been used in motion planning scenarios in robotics.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In discrete-time Markov Decision Processes, decisions are made at discrete time intervals.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] However, for **continuous-time Markov decision processes**, decisions can be made at any time the decision maker chooses.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In comparison to discrete-time Markov decision processes, continuous-time Markov decision processes can better model the decision-making process for a system that has continuous dynamics, i.e., the system dynamics are defined by ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] This modelling framework can be applied to areas such as queueing systems, epidemic processes, and population processes.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Like the discrete-time Markov decision processes, in continuous-time Markov decision processes the agent aims to find the optimal *policy* that would maximize the expected cumulative reward.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] If the state space and action space are finite, we could use linear programming to find the optimal policy, which was one of the earliest approaches applied.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Here we only consider the ergodic model, which means our continuous-time MDP becomes an ergodic continuous-time Markov chain under a stationary policy.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Under this assumption, although the decision maker can make a decision at any time in the current state, there is no benefit in taking multiple actions.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] It is better to take an action only at the time when system is transitioning from the current state to another state.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] If there exists a function h , then ${\bar {V}}^{*}$ will be the smallest g satisfying the above equation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] $y(i,a)$ is a feasible solution to the D-LP if $y(i,a)$ is nonnative and satisfied the constraints in the D-LP problem.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] for all feasible solution $y(i,a)$ to the D-LP.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Once we have found the optimal solution $y^{*}(i,a)$ , we can use it to establish the optimal policies.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In continuous-time MDP, if the state space and action space are continuous, the optimal criterion could be found by solving the Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman (HJB) partial differential equation.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] $D(\cdot )$ is the terminal reward function, $s(t)$ is the system state vector, $a(t)$ is the system control vector we try to find. $f(\cdot )$ shows how the state vector changes over time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning is an interdisciplinary area of machine learning and optimal control that has, as main objective, finding an approximately optimal policy for MDPs where transition probabilities and rewards are unknown.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Reinforcement learning can solve Markov-Decision processes without explicit specification of the transition probabilities which are instead needed to perform policy iteration.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In this setting, transition probabilities and rewards must be learned from experience, i.e. by letting an agent interact with the MDP for a given number of steps.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] While this function is also unknown, experience during learning is based on $(s,a)$ pairs (together with the outcome $s'$ ; that is, "I was in state s and I tried doing a and $s'$ happened").
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Thus, one has an array Q and uses experience to update it directly.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Another application of MDP process in machine learning theory is called learning automata.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] This is also one type of reinforcement learning if the environment is stochastic.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The first detail **learning automata** paper is surveyed by Narendra and Thathachar (1974), which were originally described explicitly as finite-state automata.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Similar to reinforcement learning, a learning automata algorithm also has the advantage of solving the problem when probability or rewards are unknown.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The difference between learning automata and Q-learning is that the former technique omits the memory of Q-values, but updates the action probability directly to find the learning result.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Learning automata is a learning scheme with a rigorous proof of convergence.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The states of such an automaton correspond to the states of a "discrete-state discrete-parameter Markov process".
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] At each time step *t* = 0,1,2,3,..., the automaton reads an input from its environment, updates P(*t*) to P(*t* + 1) by *A*, randomly chooses a successor state according to the probabilities P(*t* + 1) and outputs the corresponding action.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The automaton's environment, in turn, reads the action and sends the next input to the automaton.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Other than the rewards, a Markov decision process $(S,A,P)$ can be understood in terms of Category theory.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Namely, let ${\mathcal {A}}$ denote the free monoid with generating set *A*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Let **Dist** denote the Kleisli category of the Giry monad.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] Then a functor ${\mathcal {A}}\to \mathbf {Dist}$ encodes both the set *S* of states and the probability function *P*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In this way, Markov decision processes could be generalized from monoids (categories with one object) to arbitrary categories.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] One can call the result $({\mathcal {C}},F:{\mathcal {C}}\to \mathbf {Dist} )$ a *context-dependent Markov decision process*, because moving from one object to another in ${\mathcal {C}}$ changes the set of available actions and the set of possible states.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] The terminology and notation for MDPs are not entirely settled.
[src:markov-chains/markov-decision-process] In addition, the notation for the transition probability varies.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] In probability theory and statistics, the **Markov property** is the memoryless property of a stochastic process, which means that its future evolution is independent of its history.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] It is named after the Russian mathematician Andrey Markov.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The term **strong Markov property** is similar to the Markov property, except that the meaning of "present" is defined in terms of a random variable known as a stopping time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The term **Markov assumption** is used to describe a model where the Markov property is assumed to hold, such as a hidden Markov model.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] A Markov random field extends this property to two or more dimensions or to random variables defined for an interconnected network of items.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] An example of a model for such a field is the Ising model.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] A discrete-time stochastic process satisfying the Markov property is known as a Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] A stochastic process has the Markov property if the conditional probability distribution of future states of the process (conditional on both past and present values) depends only upon the present state; that is, given the present, the future does not depend on the past.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] A process with this property is said to be **Markov** or **Markovian** and known as a **Markov process**.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Two famous classes of Markov process are the Markov chain and Brownian motion.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Note that there is a subtle, often overlooked and very important point that is often missed in the plain English statement of the definition: the statespace of the process is constant through time.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The conditional description involves a fixed "bandwidth".
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] For example, without this restriction we could augment any process to one which includes the complete history from a given initial condition and it would be made to be Markovian.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] But the state space would be of increasing dimensionality over time and does not meet the definition.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Let $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ be a probability space with a filtration $({\mathcal {F}}_{s},\ s\in I)$ , for some (totally ordered) index set I ; and let $(S,\Sigma )$ be a measurable space.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] In other words, the distribution of X at time $n+1$ depend solely on the state of X at time n and is independent of the state of the process at any time previous to n , which corresponds precisely to the intuition described in the introduction.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The newly introduced probability measure $P^{x}(X_{t}\in \cdot )$ , $x\in S$ , has the following intuition: It gives the probability that the process X lies in some set at time t , when it was started in x at time zero.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The function $P_{t}(x,A):=P^{x}(X_{t}\in A)$ , $(t,x,A)\in \mathbb {R} _{+}\times S\times \Sigma$ , is also called the *transition function* of X and the collection $(P_{t})_{t\geq 0}$ its *transition semigroup*.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] There exists multiple alternative formulations of the elementary Markov property described above.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Depending on the situation, some formulations might be easier to verify or to use than others.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Suppose that $X=(X_{t}:t\geq 0)$ is a stochastic process on a probability space $(\Omega ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ with natural filtration $\{{\mathcal {F}}_{t}\}_{t\geq 0}$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Then X is said to have the strong Markov property if, for each stopping time $\tau$ , conditional on the event $\{\tau <\infty \}$ , we have that for each $t\geq 0$ , $X_{\tau +t}$ is independent of ${\mathcal {F}}_{\tau }$ given $X_{\tau }$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] where $1_{\{\tau <\infty \}}$ denotes to indicator function of the set $\{\tau <\infty \}$ .
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The strong Markov property implies the ordinary Markov property since by taking the stopping time $\tau =t$ , the ordinary Markov property can be deduced.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The strong Markov property only leads to non-trivial results in continuous time (i.e., results which do not hold with merely the Markov property), as in the discrete case the strong and the elementary Markov property are equivalent.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Although the strong Markov property is in general stronger than the elementary Markov property, it is fulfilled by Markov processes with sufficiently "nice" regularity properties.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] where $C_{0}(S)$ denotes the set of continuous functions vanishing at infinity and $||\cdot ||_{\infty }$ the sup norm.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Then one can show that (if the filtration is augmented) such a process has a version with right-continuous (even càdlàg) paths, which in turn fulfills the strong Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Assume that an urn contains two red balls and one green ball.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] One ball was drawn yesterday, one ball was drawn today, and the final ball will be drawn tomorrow.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] All of the draws are "without replacement".
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Suppose you know that today's ball was red, but you have no information about yesterday's ball.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] The chance that tomorrow's ball will be red is 1/2.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] On the other hand, if you know that both today and yesterday's balls were red, then you are guaranteed to get a green ball tomorrow.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] This discrepancy shows that the probability distribution for tomorrow's color depends not only on the present value, but is also affected by information about the past.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] This stochastic process of observed colors doesn't have the Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Using the same experiment above, if sampling "without replacement" is changed to sampling "with replacement," the process of observed colors will have the Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Many prominent stochastic processes are Markov processes: The Brownian motion, the Brownian bridge, the stochastic exponential, the Ornstein-Uhlenbeck process and the Poisson process have the Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] where $B=(B^{1},...,B^{d})$ is a d -dimensional Brownian motion and $f_{1},...,f_{d},g_{1},...,g_{d}:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ are autonomous (i.e., they do not depend on time) Lipschitz functions, is time-homogeneous and has the strong Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] If $f_{1},...,f_{d},g_{1},...,g_{d}$ are not autonomous, then X still has the elementary Markov property.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] In the fields of predictive modelling and probabilistic forecasting, the Markov property is considered desirable since it may enable the reasoning and resolution of the problem that otherwise would not be possible to be resolved because of its intractability.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] Such a model is known as a Markov model.
[src:markov-chains/markov-property] An application of the Markov property in a generalized form is in Markov chain Monte Carlo computations in the context of Bayesian statistics.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In mathematics, a **stochastic matrix** is a square matrix used to describe the transitions of a Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Each of its entries is a nonnegative real number representing a probability.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] It is also called a **probability matrix**, **transition matrix**, *substitution matrix*, or **Markov matrix**.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The stochastic matrix was first developed by Andrey Markov at the beginning of the 20th century, and has found use throughout a wide variety of scientific fields, including probability theory, statistics, mathematical finance and linear algebra, as well as computer science and population genetics.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In the same vein, one may define a probability vector as a vector whose elements are nonnegative real numbers which sum to 1.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Thus, each row of a right stochastic matrix (or column of a left stochastic matrix) is a probability vector.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Right stochastic matrices act upon row vectors of probabilities by multiplication from the right (hence their name) and the matrix entry in the i-th row and j-th column is the probability of transition from state i to state j.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Left stochastic matrices act upon column vectors of probabilities by multiplication from the left (hence their name) and the matrix entry in the i-th row and j-th column is the probability of transition from state j to state i.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] This article uses the right/row stochastic matrix convention.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The stochastic matrix was developed alongside the Markov chain by Andrey Markov, a Russian mathematician and professor at St.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Petersburg University who first published on the topic in 1906.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] His initial intended uses were for linguistic analysis and other mathematical subjects like card shuffling, but both Markov chains and matrices rapidly found use in other fields.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Stochastic matrices were further developed by scholars such as Andrey Kolmogorov, who expanded their possibilities by allowing for continuous-time Markov processes.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] By the 1950s, articles using stochastic matrices had appeared in the fields of econometrics and circuit theory.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In the 1960s, stochastic matrices appeared in an even wider variety of scientific works, from behavioral science to geology to residential planning.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In addition, much mathematical work was also done through these decades to improve the range of uses and functionality of the stochastic matrix and Markovian processes more generally.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] From the 1970s to present, stochastic matrices have found use in almost every field that requires formal analysis, from structural science to medical diagnosis to personnel management.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In addition, stochastic matrices have found wide use in land change modeling, usually under the term Markov matrix.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] A stochastic matrix describes a Markov chain ***X****t* over a finite state space S with cardinality α.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Since the total of transition probability from a state i to all other states must be 1, $\forall i\in \{1,\ldots ,\alpha \},\quad \sum _{j=1}^{\alpha }P_{i,j}=1;\,$ thus this matrix is a right stochastic matrix.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The above elementwise sum across each row i of P may be more concisely written as *P***1** = **1**, where **1** is the α-dimensional column vector of all ones.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In general, the k-th power *Pk* of a right stochastic matrix P is also right stochastic.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In general, the probability transition of going from any state to another state in a finite Markov chain given by the matrix P in k steps is given by *Pk*.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] An initial probability distribution of states, specifying where the system might be initially and with what probabilities, is given as a row vector.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] It can be shown that the spectral radius of any stochastic matrix is one.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] By the Gershgorin circle theorem, all of the eigenvalues of a stochastic matrix have absolute values less than or equal to one.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] More precisely, the eigenvalues of n -by- n stochastic matrices are restricted to lie within a subset of the complex unit disk, known as Karpelevič regions.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] This result was originally obtained by Fridrikh Karpelevich, following a question originally posed by Kolmogorov and partially addressed by Nikolay Dmitriyev and Eugene Dynkin.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Additionally, every right stochastic matrix has an "obvious" column eigenvector associated to the eigenvalue 1: the vector **1** used above, whose coordinates are all equal to 1.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] As left and right eigenvalues of a square matrix are the same, every stochastic matrix has, at least, a left eigenvector associated to the eigenvalue 1 and the largest absolute value of all its eigenvalues is also 1.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Finally, the Brouwer Fixed Point Theorem (applied to the compact convex set of all probability distributions of the finite set {1, ..., *n*}) implies that there is some left eigenvector which is also a stationary probability vector.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] On the other hand, the Perron–Frobenius theorem also ensures that every irreducible stochastic matrix has such a stationary vector, and that the largest absolute value of an eigenvalue is always 1.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] However, this theorem cannot be applied directly to such matrices because they need not be irreducible.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] In general, there may be several such vectors.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] where ***π**j* is the j-th element of the row vector **π**.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Among other things, this says that the long-term probability of being in a state j is independent of the initial state i.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] That both of these computations give the same stationary vector is a form of an ergodic theorem, which is generally true in a wide variety of dissipative dynamical systems: the system evolves, over time, to a stationary state.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Intuitively, a stochastic matrix represents a Markov chain; the application of the stochastic matrix to a probability distribution redistributes the probability mass of the original distribution while preserving its total mass.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] If this process is applied repeatedly, the distribution converges to a stationary distribution for the Markov chain.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Stochastic matrices and their product form a category, which is both a subcategory of the category of matrices and of the one of Markov kernels.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Suppose there is a timer and a row of five adjacent boxes.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] At time zero, a cat is in the first box, and a mouse is in the fifth box.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The cat and the mouse both jump to a random **adjacent** box when the timer advances.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] For example, if the cat is in the second box and the mouse is in the fourth, the probability that *the cat will be in the first box **and** the mouse in the fifth after the timer advances* is one fourth.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] If the cat is in the first box and the mouse is in the fifth, the probability that *the cat will be in box two and the mouse will be in box four after the timer advances* is one.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The cat eats the mouse if both end up in the same box, at which time the game ends.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Let the random variable *K* be the time the mouse stays in the game.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The Markov chain that represents this game contains the following five states specified by the combination of positions (cat,mouse).
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] We use a stochastic matrix, P (below), to represent the transition probabilities of this system (rows and columns in this matrix are indexed by the possible states listed above, with the pre-transition state as the row and post-transition state as the column).
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] For instance, starting from state 1 – 1st row – it is impossible for the system to stay in this state, so $P_{11}=0$ ; the system also cannot transition to state 2 – because the cat would have stayed in the same box – so $P_{12}=0$ , and by a similar argument for the mouse, $P_{14}=0$ .
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Transitions to states 3 or 5 are allowed, and thus $P_{13},P_{15}\neq 0$ .
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] No matter what the initial state, the cat will eventually catch the mouse (with probability 1) and a stationary state **π** = (0,0,0,0,1) is approached as a limit.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] To compute the long-term average or expected value of a stochastic variable Y , for each state $S_{j}$ and time $t_{k}$ there is a contribution of $Y_{j,k}\cdot P(S=S_{j},t=t_{k})$ .
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Survival can be treated as a binary variable with $Y=1$ for a surviving state and $Y=0$ for the terminated state.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The states with $Y=0$ do not contribute to the long-term average.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] As State 5 is an absorbing state, the distribution of time to absorption is discrete phase-type distributed.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] Suppose the system starts in state 2, represented by the vector $[0,1,0,0,0]$ .
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] The states where the mouse has perished don't contribute to the survival average so state five can be ignored.
[src:markov-chains/stochastic-matrix] where I is the identity matrix, and $\mathbf {1}$ represents a column matrix of all ones that acts as a sum over states.
